=Discussion=

==Interpretations of Nietzsche==

Cadell Last:

"Sigmund Freud: Nietzsche is a philosophical precursor to the field of psychoanalysis, with ideas related to the unconscious, repression, drives, and dreams already build into his thinking; a thinker who also deconstructs morality, criticizes Christianity as a metaphysical foundation for society, and finds truth in dimensions of the psyche that were often not even thought of before psychoanalysis; possible that Nietzsche discovered dimensions of the psyche by intuitive vision and poetic expression, which were also discovered by psychoanalysis via rational systematic inquiry.

Martin Heidegger: Nietzsche offers us a philosophy of perspectivism where objectivity is only possible after a particular value or end has been established (i.e. being-towards-x?), in this way inscribing the process of coming-to-be into objective perspectives (as a rule missing in scientific ontology/worldviews); here the loss of God as a supra-sensory ground and goal of all reality leaves humanity without an objective orientation which signals the potential end of society based on unconscious metaphysics; many of Nietzsche’s major concepts are often posed a hypotheses to burden us, as opposed to objective facts.

George Bataille: Nietzsche ends the possibility for traditional religious belief in a monotheistic God who knows everything and exists in a separate world, and opens the possibility for new idiosyncratic forms of godless mysticism hitherto unknown in the world; these new forms of mysticism should be explored in spiritual life outside of religious institutions, and may be found by thinking through abstraction as confessional (i.e. what we speak/write as a confession of our depths), and erotic life as theological (i.e. how we use/direct our sexuality as our “God”); both moves point away from the use of traditional narratives, and towards narratives allowing us to say what has never been said before/what cannot be said.  

Rene Girard: Nietzsche’s personal relationships were marked by the emotional force of resentment, and there is great evidence that his life was structured or overdetermined by mimetic (ideational) rivalries for greatness (e.g. Wagner); thus Nietzsche as a personal-historical person who struggled with madness and insanity does not stem from a physiological origin, but rather from his inability to deal with cultural conflicts and his psychological obsession with rivalry; we can see him as an extreme representative of normal human behaviour/tendencies, as well as evidence that envy and resentment still drive solitary genius.

Michel Foucault: Nietzsche’s approach and method of philosophy is the basic foundational stone for Foucaultian critical social theory, an approach and a method that allowed him to break from the “H-triad” of Hegel, Husserl, and Heidegger; this approach was based in the idea of the disunity of the subject, the will to power as constituting social knowledge, and the radical discontinuities that can emerge from subjective experimentation; this method was based in the understanding that truth is subservient to the task of active self-constitution under the will to power, and that truth rectifies itself on the basis of its own principles of self-regulation (essential for libidinal becoming outside of regimes of normative social power structure).

Albert Camus: Nietzsche was the premier diagnostician of the modern (or post-modern) human predicament, i.e. God is Dead, which was discovered existentially in the souls of his contemporaries; the consequence of this existential soul-discovery means that there is no world unity, no final judgement, no absolute or permanent values; and that we must attack/negate all attempts to fill the void, we must rather confront the void with courage; this analysis of the human condition opens us to that which is ultimately absurd, an exploration which pushes us to the most extreme forms of existence. 

Jean Paul Sartre: Nietzsche was an inspiration to approach problems of existential nihilism and the loss of objective meaning, and agreed that the question of meaning is central to the phenomenon of nihilism; ultimately committed to a form of atheism based on the idea that there is no ultimate meaning or purpose in the universe for humans and that meaning, purpose, and vales are derived from a will to power, whereas this will to power must be extended into a project-based becoming that moves the will to an unconscious in-itself, towards a self-conscious for-itself.

Ayn Rand: Nietzsche’s Thus Spoke Zarathustra replaces The Bible, and is the foundational texts that allows one to overcoming desires for suicide, allowing one to organize life to the overman as a process of self-coming; originally upset in confronting Nietzsche’s work (bitter, resentful) because Rand felt she had been beaten to all her ideas, but later strongly differentiated from Nietzsche on the basis of developing the philosophy of “objectivism”, which argued for an objective perspective for human existence, based on a rational absolute and a telos towards happiness.  

Paul Ricoeur: Nietzsche as a key part in an emerging “hermeneutics of suspicion”, where we should read texts with skepticism that exposes repressed meanings; the major figures allowing for the emergence of a hermeneutics of suspicion include also Karl Marx and Sigmund Freud (making a triad of Marx-Nietzsche-Freud that should be read together); in this school of suspicion the aim is to unmask lies or illusions of consciousness in relation to theological issues and intellectual history in general; this school opens us to a new realm of ideological critique, where we should never belief straight-forward appearances of a text, but rather read the text as inherently curved/bent/distorted from within (by the logic of capital (Marx), the will to power (Nietzsche), or unconscious symptoms (Freud)).

Gilles Deleuze: Nietzsche is presented as a systematically coherent philosopher with a systematically coherent philosophy in combining the ideas of the will to power and the eternal return; however, the will to power should not be understood as power seeking and the eternal return should not be understood as repetition of the same, the former is more about overcoming self-identity for difference, and the latter is more about understanding eternity as a process of becoming; suggests that Nietzsche is the most important philosopher since Spinoza, since both not only revolutionize theory, but also the very practice of philosophy itself.

Carl Jung: Nietzsche’s famous “God is Dead” is not a dogmatic assertion by a mad philosopher, but rather the identification of a psychological fact; Nietzsche represents the rise of psychology in its own right, a rise so strong that it threatens to swallow the whole of philosophy into itself; this rise of psychology in its own right is necessary considering that Nietzsche’s call for an individuation towards the overman was met by the emergence of new philosophical metaphysics which twisted Nietzsche into its opposite: a distorted rise of herd mentality and collectivism (e.g. fascism, communism, etc.).

Jacques Lacan: Nietzsche reveals that the totality of philosophical metaphysics is a defensive symptomal structure, not produced by a will to knowledge, but a will to not-knowing truth; the knowing of truth is rather constituted by a will to corporeal thought: speaking the symptomal knot of sexual drives for own power and a joy beyond pleasure; the will to power, its relation to joy in this life, is what is at stake in a philosophy which can include within itself psychoanalysis.

Jacques Derrida: Nietzsche is a unique philosopher insofar as he adopts a totally anti-academic style, the way he undermined the very life-ways of scholars and intellectuals; in terms of his actual philosophy, Nietzsche was capable of deconstructing the entire Kantian tradition based on experience mediated by a priori categories of mind vis-a-vis an infinite noumena, and thus we can see Nietzsche as a model for the deconstructionist canon, where we are barred from a metaphysical real of the in-itself (e.g. understandings of infinity, immortality etc.).

Nick Land: Nietzsche and also Bataille’s Nietzsche offer us an attempt to develop a shamanic psyche in the sociotechnological age, an escape from philosophical conceptualization for ulterior zones, a total abandonment of “things-in-themselves”, whether a religious monotheist God, or the Kantian noumenal thing of ultimate reality; here we can move towards a-categorical invisible splendours, immense deathscapes without images, and a beyond of all integral truths.

Daniel Dennett: Nietzsche, in contrast to the interpretations of post-structuralist and deconstructionist accounts of Nietzsche, can be thought of as working in the same tradition and direction as a Darwinian science; Nietzsche’s ideas of social morality are fundamentally evolutionary in nature, and can be rooted and extended in pre-human sociobiological conflict; while Nietzsche’s philosophy as a whole is against a type of naive scientific objectivity, his work is still consistent with an evolutionary picture of the universe.

Max More: Nietzsche’s nihilism is only a transitory stage between the breakdown of religious interpretations of the world and the emergence of the transhuman being; we can interpret Nietzsche’s overman as the meaning of the earth in a modern scientific and technological way, where heroic self-transformation through overcoming what we are, i.e. radical contempt for our inherited evolutionary history and biological condition, is essentially connected to the potentials of 21st century transhumanism.

Peter Sloterdijk: Nietzsche represents a catastrophe in the history of language, ushering us into an age of narcissistic jubilation and ecstasy, forcing upon us the end of humility, abandonment of all sobriety for megalomaniacal individualism which no defines and destroys contemporary philosophy; this interpretations is generated through his focus on Thus Spoke Zarathustra and the way it can be seen as Nietzsche’s attempt at an egoic-individualist ‘fifth Gospel’.

Alain Badiou: Nietzsche represents the ultimate anti-philosophy, a singular explosion of madness which opposes speculative nihilism for the radical act, here Nietzsche organizes his work under seven names coding difference forces as truth (e.g. Christ, Dionysus, Saint Paul, Socrates, Wagner, Zarathustra, and Nietzsche himself); the supreme act of the prophet, actor and name together end Christian enslavement to morality and reverses/transvaluates all values as a first politics, not as a political project in-itself.

Alenka Zupancic: Nietzsche is a philosopher whose time has finally come only insofar as we view Nietzsche as someone who is unfashionable and out-of-place in any time, a metapsychologist who oscillates between idealism and nihilism, overdetermining the present society with a postmodern hedonism; ultimately a Nietzschean philosophy can only be articulated, not as a unity of all things under the overman, but as the moment of a splitting of one into two, ushering us into an era of irreducible difference and tension, the interpretation and motor of overcoming postmodern hedonism itself.


I think, as complex as this field may appear, it can be meta-organized in four basic categories:

* New Nietzschean Metaphysics (spirit beyond religious in-itself)
* Nietzsche’s End of Metaphysics (abandonment of in-itself)
* Nietzsche as Diagnostician (modern human condition)
* Nietzsche as Madman (false philosophical turn). "

